reviewText: This is a must own dvd for anyone with a good work out collection. Denise really gets your heart going in this one. Don't be fooled into thinking there is any actual kick boxing but she does get the whole body moving with punches and round houses. Some don't like her bubbly nature, but it really gets me going. She also does the best cool down out there.

reviewText: I originally had this on VHS and now I have it on DVD.  This is one of Denise's worst workouts for cueing.  She has gotten better with that I think in more recent ones, but after a few times, you know what the next move is so it doesn't really matter.  I like it because I can just jump in and work up a great sweat in 20 minutes.  This does have high impact moves in it such as jumping jacks.  I have arthritic knees and modify any high impact moves, but it does not take away from raising my heart rate.  The second workout adds variety with light weights for cross training.  So if you want to just jump in and start sweating, try these workouts.
summary: Yes, bad cueing but fun and effective for 20 minutes

reviewText: I should begin by saying that I've never liked Denise; I used to see her TV show years ago, and I just always found her raspy voice and fake (to me) enthusiasm to be annoying.  However, I like both kickboxing and interval workouts, so I decided to be open-minded and give this video a try. The two workouts on this video are each approximately 22 minutes in length; I'm guessing that they were taken from Denise's TV show, but the commercial breaks have been nicely smoothed over.The first program is called Kickbox Blast Off.  Prior to the start of the workout, Denise briefly reviews the different punches, which was helpful.  The workout itself begins with a simple warm up which includes punches, moves on to some standing abs work (twists), and then goes into kick-punch combinations.  The kickboxing work is low impact, but unfortunately, Denise throws in quite a few jacks; I could have done without these.  I definitely enjoyed the kickboxing combos, but Denise's exceptionally poor cueing really detracted from the workout:  she suddenly goes into new moves and combos with absolutely no warning or instruction.  At times, I found myself looking to her six background exercisers for guidance (they often displayed better form anyway), but even they were obviously having trouble following Denise.  Towards the end of the workout, there is some focused leg toning work, and then it ends with a 3-minute Tai Chi-like cool down.The second program is called Interval Workout With Weights.  In this workout, Denise alternates 3-minute cardio intervals with 1-minute light toning intervals.  After the 3-minute warm-up, the first cardio segment was somewhat dancey and included mambos and chassés.  The first toning interval focused on shoulders, and then it was back to cardio for a kickboxing segment.  Next came biceps work, another dancey cardio interval, back and triceps work, and then a final kickboxing interval prior to the 4-minute cool-down.  The workout is mostly low-impact, but Denise does include some jacks and plyometric moves.  Although Denise's cueing was again off, she repeats many of the moves, so I was eventually able to follow along.  This workout did nicely raise my heart rate, but I felt that the toning segments were pretty inconsequential (using heavier weights would help).  There are only two background exercisers in this segment.If these two workouts were led by a different instructor, I probably would have really enjoyed them, but Denise's poor cueing and form definitely had a negative impact.  These workouts are probably best suited to advanced beginners; I'm more in the intermediate category, but using my 1-lb. weighted gloves during both workouts increased the intensity for me.  I'm glad I gave this video a shot, but at this point, I probably would not be willing to work out with Denise again.
summary: Two mostly solid workouts but with some major caveats

reviewText: I have had this video for a few years and it is still a good workout.  I am an intermediate/advanced excerciser and workout about 5-6 times a week.  When I first started dong this video my heart was pumping and still does...primarily on the first half of the video.The video is 2 20 minute sections but the kickboxing routine feels more of a workout than the interval training with weights(2nd half of video).  The routines are not hard and I think these are more beginner/intermediate work outs.My only gripe is that since the second routine is interval training it would have been nice to have more cardio popping excercises and to be able to use the weights more than 3 times for the interval training.As with many of her DVD's Denises cueing is off primarily in the first routine which is the cardio kickboxing but it is still a good work out.  At this time I use this DVD more for a low/medium impact workout.

reviewText: This tape is most effective when you do both the 20 minute segments. The moves are easy to follow after you'd done them a few times.  (Despite Denise's not-so-good counting and cues)I work out five times a week and I switch off between this tape and Denise's Ultimate Fat Burner tape. I dropped a few pounds after only a week of using them and noticed some muscle definition in my arms and thighs. Circuit training is really the way to go if you want to lose weight effectively. This tape will give you a great workout and I highly recommend it.

reviewText: I bought this video cause it sounded nice if you were crunched for time, and it is that I suppose.  I felt like in the first 20 minutes I got a good workout.  The second 20 minutes wasn't as good, and the weight lifting segments seemed useless.The biggest problem I had was I could not stand the instructor.  It's been mentioned that she can't cue to save her life, which is true.  You hear a lot of "now one more" followed by her doing 2 or 3 more.  It's like her body is not connected to her mouth, or something.  But the cuing wasn't the worst part.  Her constant blabbering really got to me.  I think she was trying to be motivating, but all it motivated me to do was turn off the tape.  I got tired of hearing, "you're doing great", "you're going to look so good", "god only gave you one body"--NONSTOP.  And she talked in this quiet patronizing tone, the kind you would use to talk to a disobedient child who you wanted to calm down.  I might suggest trying it without the sound--I think that's the only way this video could be handled.

reviewText: I will admit to being a Denise Austin fan.  She's one of the few workout gurus who seems to get that not everyone has 2 hours a day to devote to a gym, and she often incorporates small moves to integrate into your daily routine to build muscle, etc.  I appreciates that she realizes normal people live typical lives that sometimes don't allow for a daily trip to the gym.  Plus, being in her early/mid 40s, I find her very motivating as I approach middle age.That being said, I'm used to Denise Austin and her bad cuing, which this tape is typical miscue-Denise.  The workouts are great, they definitely get your heart pumping and you feel like you've gotten a workout.  But you need to work out to the tape a few times so you can get the movements down.  If you have to have cues, this tape can be unreliable.  Some are late, some are apparently missed...but it's typical Denise Austin.  You have to be familliar with her style or it will turn you away.So, I would recommend this tape highly on the basis of a vigorous, time-sensitive workout and that it has a 'warm-up/beginner' level, and a secondary level that you can do for a more intense workout or as you are increasing your activity.  But you will have to watch it a few times before you get the feel of it, because if you have to rely solely on cues, you will get frustrated with this tape, initially.

reviewText: When I tried this the first few times, I wasn't that impressed.  I was sweating and my heart rate got up, but I didn't feel that it was how I wanted to be spending my 20 minute aerobic session.  I left it alone for a month, then tried it again out of boredom (and because it seemed silly to buy something else when I had this right in front of me).  Absence must have made the heart grow fonder- I really enjoyed it this time.  The next day I worked out to the Tae Bo Live Basic for a full 13 minutes longer and I was shocked to find that Billy didn't give me nearly as thorough a workout as Denise.  I've been doing this tape consistently once or twice a week, and I can definitely feel my aerobic capacity and general stamina improving.As with all tapes, watch this at least once before you do it.  She doesn't cue very well in some places, and it can be a little frustrating.  However, I think I'd rather have her keep me on my toes the first few times than get frustrated one month into it with over-cuing.I prefer the first workout to the second because I like to do different exercises for my strength training.  I did do the interval workout once and found it adequate.

reviewText: I am not upset because I picked this copy up at the salvation army for .99.  I have never not liked a Denise Austin video because her stuff is my style: basic exercise moves.  Not this one.  In the first of the two it is way too fast for me to keep up.  It was not what I was expecting.  I was expecting what was in the second work out.  The first one is an actual kickboxing routine like Tae Bo.  The second has kick boxing moves in it, but isn't a kickboxing class.  Needless to say I like the second one and not the first.  On this one I have to say her cueing was off even for her dancers and it was just way too fast to keep up doing it her way.  I did get a great sweaty workout though, as she was doing her thing I was doing mine with knee lifts, kicks, etc.  I will try it again but with my rebounder for some of the non kicking and non jabbing moves because I hate all that jumping.  If it doesn't work for me with the rebounder I will just use part two for sure only. It actually suprised me because even when she does an "in" theme she usually makes it into a basic exercise routine.  Not with this one. I think I am coordinated but this one is just too fast. From the sweat I broke I do think it is good cardio though.I am so glad that I only paid .99 cents.

reviewText: This workout is great for people on the go and can only spare the 20 minutes the two segments offer. Every time I do the workout, I break a sweat and feel like I'm using my short workout time wisely. Denise Austin does have some problems with cueing but once you learn the routine it does not affect your workout. The circuit training section is not very intense but if you do both workouts together the kicks punches and jabs make up for it. The only thing I do not like is she tends to explain moves while she's doing them (not before) so I got lost a couple of times. reviewText: This workout dvd is great as far as the actual workout goes but it was lacking good instruction from Denise whose tapes are generally well done. One minute you are performing one particular move, then without warning you have to move onto something else with no notice as she doesn't count out how many repetitions are left to go, or what comes next (to get you prepared). If you aren't distracted by the exercisers in this tape also not knowing what comes next (some don't catch on right away while others have started moves Denise hasn't started yet) then the workout itself will help you burn calories and for that alone it's worth the money.

reviewText: I have to say I hate Denise Austin's style. Her cueing is the WORST I have ever seen. Throughout the tape she is constantly getting off of the beat, doing fewer reps of a particular move than she originally said to do, and so on. It is so bad that even the cast in this workout gets confused several times, and does the wrong move at the wrong time. However, like I said it does make you sweat and it does have some 'fun factor' with the kicks and punches. Also it is great if you are in a time crunch or if you want to add a 20 minutes extra minutes of cardio, in addition to your regular workout. This workout is not for the novice though, it gets the heart rate up pretty high, and requires good ab and back strength. I would say it was fine for intermediate exercisers, and beginners could do this too, with modifications.
summary: This workout makes you sweat, but...

reviewText: I have never done any kickboxing before so it took about five viewings before I got Denise's routine down.  It would probably have been easier if Denise would learn to cue her viewers better.  Her count is not much better. Denise needs to view Crunch Fat Burning Pilates and take some lessons from Ellen Barrett about proper cuing and keeping count.  Once I got use to the bad cuing the kick boxing section was really awesome.  It had my heart rate up and I was sweating like crazy when it was over.  The interval training was not very interesting or fun.  I thought it would keep up the same heart pumping workout from the kicking boxing section of the tape, but it didn't.  The second section was more of a dance workout with weights.  I have only done the second section once, but maybe if I do it a few more times I will start enjoy it, but I doubt it; besides it requires more workout space than I have available, unlike the kickboxing section which enabled me to work within the limited space of my room. If your library has this workout tape, burrow it and see if you like it.  If I had done that I would not have bought it, despite the great kickboxing workout.
summary: Kickboxing Section Great! Interval Training So-so

reviewText: As a new mom, going to school full time for my master's degree, working part time, keeping a house presentable, etc., etc., and 20 pounds still to lose, I bought this video because of the two 20 minute workout segments.  I need effective, short workouts.  This video provided exactly what I was looking for.  The first segment is harder than the second, and I was happy to read from other reviewers that I was not the only one stumbling around my living room during the first half.  But, it is not impossible and I will get it down soon.  The second half provides some good weight workouts in combination with aerobics.  If I have more time, I will skip the cool down in the first half and treat both parts as one.  I've used Tae Bo for several years and find these twenty minute segments to be just as if not more effective than the Basic Tae Bo 20+ minute video.  The arrangement of moves makes more sense in this video than in the Tae Bo video as well.  I enjoyed this video and recommend it to other time crunched individuals.  Of note:  The production quality of the video is pretty poor--this doesn't take away from the workout, but if production is important to you, keep looking.

reviewText: I find this DVD to be one of Denise Austin's best cardio workouts. The DVD contains two workouts: the first, a kickboxing workout; the second, an interval cardio workout with 5 pound hand-weights. Both workouts are 20 minutes in length.The kickboxing workout is of high intensity. It always makes me sweat. Unlike some of Denise's interval training workouts, you don't really get any recovery time. Instead of "relaxing" with a light jogging motion you are doing jacks. This is wonderful if you want an intense workout but probably not ideal for people looking to start exercising after a lull.The interval strength training workout is predominantly a cardio workout. You utilize hand-weights but only for about a quarter to a third of the workout session. Denise has incorporated a few very basic dance moves into this workout, something I found a great deal of fun. This cardio is not as intense as in the kickboxing segment but, never the less, delivers and excellent workout.Many people have commented on Denise's poor cuing in this DVD. Denise is always excellent with enthusiasm but has never been good with cuing. This DVD is no different. If you *watch* the DVD instead of just listening for vocal cues you will be fine. Also, after doing the workout three times you will get an idea of how moves will progress and cuing will not be an issue.I highly recommend this DVD for its excellent cardio segments.

reviewText: I had read some of the reviews when this was on VHS, and when it came out on DVD, I decided to chance my arm on it since I am a Denise Austin fan andhave enjoyed all of her DVDs thus far.I was not disappointed with the intensity of the workout.  There are two workouts on this DVD, the first being a 20min Kickboxing Blast Off (or something along those lines), which is essentially 20 minutes of kickboxing cardio, where short combos are performed for a few minutes each.  In the first workout, she alternates combos with short bursts of plyometrics, and I'm very pleased about this since previously my only experience with plyometrics was in Denise Austin's "Ultimate Fat Burner", which at 45min length, isn't the pinnacle of convenience.Be warned though - I own a lot of Denise Austin's DVDs, and I'll have to say that her cueing is at its very worst in this workout.  In general, people should know by now that Denise isn't the best at cueing, but in this workout she is bad even for her below-par cueing standards.  I personally purchase DVDs so that I can do them enough times to not need cueing and instruction, but I do know that other people are not so laid back and relaxed about instruction so if you are picky, then don't even bother with any Denise Austin workout.Her cueing is better in the second workout on the DVD, which is 20mins of Interval training.  She alternates a few minutes of cardio with a few minutes of strength training.  Denise uses 5 pound weights, but I use 3 pound simply because I haven't been able to find any 5 pound weights in New Zealand (I have found a pair of 8 pound weights though, which is a bit strange!).  Overall I find this less fun than the first workout, but my Mum really likes it because the short toning bursts gives a few moments to recover from intense cardio.I always find myself itching to do one of these workouts, and probably the most pleasing thing for myself is that I always sleep like a baby after doing them; Denise really makes me work hard!If you are able to forgive Denise for her bubbly personality, her bad cueing, and if you are able to forgive the crazy disco muzak and art deco set, then I highly recommend this DVD.
summary: Fun, energising and addictive kickboxing cardio!

reviewText: Blast Away the Fat is a great way for begginers to lose weight, for regular exercises who are struggling to lose those last 10 lbs., or to just throw in your regular cardio rotation.It's 2 different workouts, both 20 minutes long. The first one focuses more on cardio through kickboxing intervals, it also works the legs with lots of lunges and jumping around. The second workout is interval training combining kickboxing moves with free weights. Overall, Denise's cueing is disastrous, which is strange since she has so much experience and has been an instructor forever... That being said, the workout is great for burning calories, breaking a good sweat and working your legs. You'll definitely get your heart rate up and sweat.This workout is easy to squeeze in a busy day and chances are the next day your legs will be sore. Denise does talk a lot, although I do find some of her words very kind and motivating, but I generally tune her out and focus on my workout.
summary: Sweat and burn fat for real...

reviewText: This was my first Denise Austin workout dvd and it was very disappointing. I've been using many other workout dvd's done by excellent instructors (Tamilee Webb, Michelle Dozois, Lara Hudson, and Ellen Barrett specifically) and I must say that Denise falls way behind these other instructors in her overall quality of instruction and cueing. In this dvd, there is NO cueing whatsover. Not only was I confused and frusterated trying to keep up, the exercisers in the dvd also seemed like they aren't sure what's coming next. reviewText: This DVD has a rather complicated way to access the sessions. The first page has a picture of Denise and on the right side, PLAY ALL is underlined, making it clickable, and under that is the word Chapters. If you click on PLAY ALL, you are playing the entire 11 chapters back to back. If you click on Chapters, you get a list of clickable individual chapters numbered from 1 to 11, each 10 minutes long. All are titled. However if you click on chapter 3, it doesn't start over counting minutes. It starts at 7 minutes, and so on. So it is not user friendly. This DVD is not for beginners. there is a lot of kick boxing, punching, high steps, jumping jacks, jumping in place--might be fun for a 4 year old, but a little boring for an adult, not to mention tiring. Last strike--no warm up or cool down. I used another Denise Austin DVD for my 5 minute warm up and cool down that I like very much. But I had to change DVDs, sit through both DVDs, yada yada yada---It also looked "thrown together lets make some more money". Just didn't care for it, compared to some of the others she has done.

reviewText: I used to do this workout on VHS and I'm glad Denise released it on DVD because it is a gem. Despite the macabre art-deco set, Crisco-Disco Muzak, non-existent cueing, and confused-looking participants, this workout is a lot of fun.Denise bobs, weaves, hooks, punches, and kicks her way through the first 20-minutes of this 2-part program, followed by another 20-minutes of interval training (low-impact aerobics/kickboxing alternating with 5 lbs. free-weight exercises for the shoulders, back, and arms). I skip the tai-chi cooldown at the end of the first portion and go to the second part so I can do it as a single workout (another perk of having this on DVD). This workout really gets the heart-rate up and you can feel the "burn" all over your body. I am astounded that while I'm breathless and panting, Denise is maintaining a steady, effortless, reassuring patter (she is in great shape!).The moves are simple and straightforward. The lack of cueing might be a problem if you're only doing this workout once; but if you plan on doing it regularly, it will become very easy to follow. Although some people dislike Denise's chatter and childlike expressions ("don't let your tummy ploop down!"), I find her to be very soothing during a difficult, painful workout. With nearly a dozen of her DVDs, she's almost like a friend who comes right to my house everyday and helps keep me in shape!
summary: An Older VHS Favorite Now on DVD!
